]] (born 1937), American computer scientist, creator of the early video game ''Spacewar!'', nicknamed Slug\n* [[Slug Signorino]], illustrator and designer Michele Signorino, most notable for his cartoons in ''The Straight Dope''\n* [[Casimir Witucki]] (1928\u20132015), American National Football League player, nicknamed Slug\n\n==Other uses==\n* \"Slug road\", a colloquial name for the [[A957 road]]way in eastern Scotland, UK\n* Slug, a synonym for [[punch (combat)]]\n* The Slug, a derogatory nickname for [[The Cloud, Auckland]], a multi-purpose event venue in Auckland, New Zealand\n\n==See also==\n* [[Slugger (disambiguation)]]\n* [[Slugging]], a carpooling \n\n{{disambig}}\n[[Category:Lists of people by nickname]]\n", "name_user": "Jo-Jo Eumerus", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing link(s):Wikipedia:Articles for deletion/Slug Signorinoclosed as delete (XFDcloser)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slug_(disambiguation)"}
{"title_page": "2007\u201308 NBA season", "text_new": "{{Infobox sports season\n| title            =2007\u201308 NBA season\n| league           =[[National Basketball Association]]\n| sport            =[[Basketball]]\n| logo             =\n| pixels           =\n| caption          =\n| duration         =October 30, 2007 \u2013 April 16, 2008 <br> April 19 \u2013 May 30, 2008 (Playoffs) <br> June 5 \u2013 17, 2008 (Finals)\n| no_of_games      =82\n| no_of_teams      =30\n| attendance       =\n| TV               =[[NBA on ABC|ABC]], [[NBA on TNT|TNT]], [[NBA on ESPN|ESPN]], [[NBA TV]]\n| draft            =Draft\n| draft_link       =2007 NBA draft\n| top_pick         =[[Greg Oden]] (did not play until 2008\u201309 season)\n| top_pick_link    =List of first overall NBA draft picks\n| picked_by        =[[Portland Trail Blazers]]\n| season           =Regular season\n| top_seed         =[[Boston Celtics]]\n| MVP              =[[Kobe Bryant]] ([[Los Angeles Lakers|L.A. Lakers]])\n| MVP_link         =NBA Most Valuable Player Award \n| top_scorer       =[[LeBron James]] ([[Cleveland Cavaliers|Cleveland]])\n| top_scorer_link  =List of National Basketball Association season scoring leaders\n| playoffs         =Playoffs\n| playoffs_link    =2008 NBA playoffs\n| conf1            =Eastern\n| conf1_link       =Eastern Conference (NBA)\n| conf1_champ      =Boston Celtics\n| conf1_runner-up  =[[Detroit Pistons]]\n| conf2            =Western\n| conf2_link       =Western Conference (NBA)\n| conf2_champ      =Los Angeles Lakers\n| conf2_runner-up  =[[San Antonio Spurs]]\n| finals           =Finals\n| finals_link      =2008 NBA Finals\n| finals_champ     =Boston Celtics\n| finals_runner-up =Los Angeles Lakers\n| finals_MVP       =[[Paul Pierce]] (Boston)\n| finals_MVP_link  =Bill Russell NBA Finals Most Valuable Player Award \n| seasonslist      =List of NBA seasons\n| seasonslistnames =NBA\n| prevseason_link  =2006\u201307 NBA season\n| prevseason_year  =2006\u201307\n| nextseason_link  =2008\u201309 NBA season\n| nextseason_year  =2008\u201309}}\nThe '''2007\u201308 NBA season''' was the 62nd season of the [[National Basketball Association]]. The [[Boston Celtics]] defeated the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] 131\u201392 to win the [[2008 NBA Finals]], four games to two. The [[2007 NBA draft]] was held on June 28, 2007 and [[Greg Oden]] was selected first overall by the [[Portland Trail Blazers]].  However, he missed the entire season due to knee surgery.<ref>[http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2007/basketball/nba/wires/09/13/2030.ap.bkn.trail.blazers.oden.2nd.ld.writethru.0726/index.html Top draft pick Greg Oden to miss rookie season with Trail Blazers], ''Sports Illustrated''.</ref>\n\nThis season was notable for being one of the most competitive [[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]] playoff races in NBA history. Up until April 4, 2008, not a single Western Conference team had secured a playoff spot, and the 8th-seeded team was a mere 6.5 games behind the 1st seed. Additionally, the quality of the teams ensured that the [[2007\u201308 Golden State Warriors season|Golden State Warriors]] finished with the highest winning percentage of any non-playoff team in NBA history since the switch to the eight-team playoff format, beating out the [[2000\u201301 Houston Rockets season|2000\u201301 Houston Rockets]]. This was later tied by the [[2013\u201314 Phoenix Suns season|2013\u201314 Phoenix Suns]]. The all-time record is held by the [[1971\u201372 Phoenix Suns season|1971\u201372 Phoenix Suns]] (49\u201333), which was during the four-team playoff era.\n\n==Notable occurrences==\n\n*The [[2008 NBA All-Star Game]] was played at the [[New Orleans Arena]], home of the [[New Orleans Hornets]], on February 17, 2008 with the East winning 134-128 and [[Cleveland Cavaliers|Cleveland's]] [[LeBron James]] being named the MVP. Every single All-Star Game participant would end up in the NBA playoffs, with the exception of [[Brandon Roy]] of the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] and [[Dwyane Wade]] of the [[Miami Heat]].\n*The Hornets returned to [[New Orleans, Louisiana]] full-time, after splitting home games during the previous two seasons with New Orleans and [[Oklahoma City]] due to damage caused by [[Hurricane Katrina]].\n*The NBA extended its six-year television contract with [[Time Warner]]'s [[Turner Network Television|TNT]] and [[The Walt Disney Company]]'s [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] and [[ESPN]] through 2016.\n*[[Sacramento Kings]] small forward [[Ron Artest]] and [[Golden State Warriors]] shooting guard [[Stephen Jackson]] were suspended for the first seven games of the season.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2936623 Jackson, Artest suspended following court pleas], ESPN.</ref>\n*The [[Orlando Magic]] got approvals in the last week of July for a [[Amway Center|new arena]], which was ready for the 2010\u201311 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/community/news/downtown/orl-venues2407jul24,0,2226250.story?coll=orl_tab01_layout |title=Orlando OKs venues; big hurdle awaits  |access-date=2007-10-27 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071113155829/http://www.orlandosentinel.com/community/news/downtown/orl-venues2407jul24,0,2226250.story?coll=orl_tab01_layout |archive-date=2007-11-13 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*After spending 12 seasons with the [[Minnesota Timberwolves]], [[Kevin Garnett]] was traded to the Boston Celtics in exchange for seven different players, the largest trade in NBA history for one player.\n*On November 2, 2007, the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] made their plans to move to [[Oklahoma City]] official.<ref name=\"Sonics move\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3091416 |title=Sonics tell NBA of intent to move SuperSonics to Oklahoma City |agency=Associated Press |publisher=ESPN.com |date=2007-11-03 |accessdate=2007-12-27}}</ref>\n*On December 23, 2007, [[Kobe Bryant]] became the youngest player to score 20,000 points at age 29 years, 122 days old, surpassing [[Wilt Chamberlain]]'s previous record of 29 years, 134 days old.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kobe Bryant Reaches 20,000-Point Plateau|url=http://www.nba.com/news/kbryant_20000_points.html|date=2007-12-23|work=[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]|accessdate=2007-12-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101231042720/http://www.nba.com/news/kbryant_20000_points.html|archive-date=2010-12-31|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*On December 24, 2007, the [[Chicago Bulls]] fired head coach [[Scott Skiles]] after a 9\u201316 start. [[Jim Boylan]] was named the interim head coach for the remaining games in the season three days later.<ref>{{cite news |title=Sports People: Chicago Bulls fire coach Scott Skiles |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/cs-071224chicagobullsfirecoachscottskiles,0,6113811.story?coll=chi-site-nav |date=2007-12-24 |work=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=2007-12-25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071228064524/http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/cs-071224chicagobullsfirecoachscottskiles%2C0%2C6113811.story?coll=chi-site-nav |archivedate=2007-12-28 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*On January 11, 2008, NBA commissioner [[David Stern]] granted the Miami Heat a 51.9-second replay on their overtime game on December 19, 2007 versus the [[Atlanta Hawks]] because the official scorer ruled incorrectly that [[Shaquille O'Neal]] was fouled out, when he was on his fifth foul. The Hawks were fined $50,000 for their \"gross negligence\". The replay was held on March 8, 2008, before the teams' next meeting. This was the first replay since December 1982 when then-NBA commissioner [[Larry O'Brien]] granted a replay on a double overtime game between the [[San Antonio Spurs]] and the Los Angeles Lakers.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3192421 Heat, Hawks to replay final minute of Dec. 19 game later this year], ESPN.</ref> This replay was continued despite O'Neal having been traded to the [[Phoenix Suns]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/nba_news/replay_080304.html NBA Sets Guidelines for Heat-Hawks Replay], NBA.com</ref> The Hawks went on to win the replay.\n*February 2008 was marked by several major trades by some the league's top teams.  Some of the more notable trades include:\n**[[Pau Gasol]] going from the [[Memphis Grizzlies]] to the Los Angeles Lakers for [[Kwame Brown]], [[Javaris Crittenton]], [[Aaron McKie]], draft rights to his brother [[Marc Gasol]], and two first-round draft picks in 2008 and 2010.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=3226203 In dire need of frontcourt help, Lakers acquire Gasol from Grizzlies], ''ESPN''.</ref>\n**[[Shaquille O'Neal]] going from the Miami Heat to the Phoenix Suns in return for [[Shawn Marion]] and [[Marcus Banks]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/suns/news/release_080206.html Suns trade Marion and Banks for O'Neal to the Heat], ''NBA''.</ref>\n**[[Mike Bibby]] going from the [[Sacramento Kings]] to the Atlanta Hawks in exchange for [[Anthony Johnson (basketball)|Anthony Johnson]], [[Tyronn Lue]], [[Shelden Williams]], [[Lorenzen Wright]], and a second-round [[2008 NBA draft|2008 draft pick]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/hawks/news/Hawks_Acquire_Bibby_021608.html |title=HAWKS: Hawks Acquire Mike Bibby From Sacramento |accessdate=2008-02-17| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20080220061523/http://www.nba.com/hawks/news/Hawks_Acquire_Bibby_021608.html| archivedate= 20 February 2008 | url-status= live}}</ref>\n**[[Jason Kidd]], along with [[Malik Allen]] and [[Antoine Wright (basketball player)|Antoine Wright]] going from the [[New Jersey Nets]] to the [[Dallas Mavericks]] in exchange for [[Devin Harris]], [[DeSagana Diop]], [[Maurice Ager]], [[Trenton Hassell]], retired [[Keith Van Horn]], two first-round draft picks and three million dollars.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/mavericks/news/Kidd_trade_021908.html Mavs acquire Kidd from Nets], ''NBA''.</ref>\n**[[Kurt Thomas (basketball)|Kurt Thomas]] going from the [[Seattle SuperSonics]] to the [[San Antonio Spurs]] in exchange for [[Brent Barry]], [[Francisco Elson]] and a 2009 first-round draft pick.  Brent Barry was immediately waived by the Sonics, and later re-signed by the Spurs.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/spurs/news/spurs_obtain_kurt_thomas_080220.html Duncan receives help, Spurs trade Elson and Barry for Thomas], ''NBA''.</ref>\n**A three-team deal between [[Cleveland Cavaliers|Cleveland]], [[Chicago Bulls|Chicago]], and Seattle that saw [[Ben Wallace]] and [[Joe Smith (basketball)|Joe Smith]], a 2009 second-round pick, Sonics forward [[Wally Szczerbiak]] and guard [[Delonte West]] all go to Cleveland, Cavs forwards [[Drew Gooden]] and [[Cedric Simmons]], guards [[Larry Hughes]] and [[Shannon Brown]] go to Chicago, Cavs forwards [[Ira Newble]] and [[Donyell Marshall]], and Bulls forward [[Adrian Griffin]] go to Seattle.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/hughes_gooden_080221.html  three-way trade deal for Chicago, Cleveland, and Seattle] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080306200219/http://www.nba.com/bulls/news/hughes_gooden_080221.html |date=2008-03-06 }}, ''NBA''.</ref>\n**[[Bonzi Wells]] and [[Mike James (basketball, born 1975)|Mike James]] going from the [[Houston Rockets]] to the [[New Orleans Hornets]] for [[point guard]] [[Bobby Jackson (basketball)|Bobby Jackson]].<ref>[http://www.nba.com/hornets/news/HORNETS_ACQUIRE_WELLS_AND_JAME-258879-31.html Hornets acquire Wells and James/Jackson reunited with Adelman], ''NBA''.</ref>\n*On February 28, 2008, [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]' [[LeBron James]] became the youngest player to score 10,000 points at age 23 years, 59 days old, surpassing [[Kobe Bryant]]'s previous record of 24 years, 193 days old.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=nba&id=3268130 James hits milestone but Cavaliers fall to Celtics 92-87], ESPN.</ref>\n*From January 29, 2008 to March 18, 2008, the [[Houston Rockets]] won 22 consecutive games, notching the [[List of National Basketball Association longest winning streaks|fourth longest winning streak]] in NBA history.\n*The Boston Celtics broke the record for the best single-season turnaround in [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] history by improving from 24 wins in [[2006\u201307 NBA season|2006\u201307]] to 66 wins this season, a total of 42 games.<ref>Mark Murphy, [http://www.bostonherald.com/sports/basketball/celtics/view.bg?articleid=1085270&srvc=celt&position=1 C\u2019s can do as they please - Stars sit, but team still clinches homecourt], ''[[Boston Herald]]'', April 6, 2008.</ref> The previous record of 36 games was held by the [[1997\u201398 San Antonio Spurs season|1997\u201398 San Antonio Spurs]], who improved from 20 to 56 wins.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=280405030 No Big Three, but Celts still get top seed, complete NBA's biggest turnaround], [[Associated Press]], April 5, 2008.</ref><ref>Lisa Brooks, [http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/dailydime?page=dime-080403 Celtics: From Worst To First], ''[[ESPN.com]]'', April 2, 2008.</ref>\n*The Atlanta Hawks made the playoffs for the first time since [[1998\u201399 NBA season|1999]], ending [[List of NBA franchise post-season droughts|the league's longest playoff drought]].<ref>[https://sports.yahoo.com/nba/news;_ylt=AhtaAf_zB88QqffBQOxl6Ku8vLYF?slug=ap-hawks-playoffs&prov=ap&type=lgns Hawks returning to NBA playoffs for first time in 9 years], [[Associated Press]], April 14, 2008.</ref>\n*The [[Golden State Warriors]] missed the playoffs despite finishing the regular season with a 48-34 record.\n*On April 28, 2008, [[Pat Riley]] announced that he would step down as the Miami Heat head coach after leading the team to a 15-67 record. Former Heat assistant coach [[Erik Spoelstra]] was announced as his replacement. Riley remained as team president.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/heat/news/riley_spoelstra_080428.html Riley Steps Down, Spoelstra Named Head Coach], ''NBA'', April 28, 2008, accessed April 28, 2008.</ref>\n*The [[New Orleans Hornets]] (now the Pelicans) won their team's first playoff series in franchise history defeating the [[Dallas Mavericks]] 4-1. They lost a seven-game series to the [[San Antonio Spurs]] in the conference semifinals.\n*After losing in the first round of the playoffs, [[Dallas Mavericks]] coach [[Avery Johnson]] was fired as head coach. Former Pacers coach [[Rick Carlisle]] was named as Johnson's replacement.\n*[[Mike D'Antoni]] agreed to a four-year, $24 million contract with the [[New York Knicks]]. The team D'Antoni left, the Phoenix Suns, replaced him with [[Terry Porter]].\n*The [[2008 NBA Finals]] featured No. 1 seeds from both conferences for the first time since [[2000 NBA Finals|2000]]. The Boston Celtics, who earned their first finals appearance since [[1987 NBA Finals|1987]], faced the Los Angeles Lakers, reviving a classic rivalry not seen since the Lakers beat the Celtics 4-2 in 1987.  This time the Celtics prevailed 4\u20132 over the Lakers.\n*[[Flip Saunders]] was dismissed as [[Detroit Pistons]] head coach, four days after the Celtics beat the Pistons in the Eastern Conference Finals.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/pistons/news/saunders_080603.html Flip Saunders Not To Return As Pistons\u2019 Coach], ''NBA'', June 3, 2008, accessed June 3, 2008.</ref>\n*On June 17, 2008, after a rough 26-game journey, the Boston Celtics won their record 17th NBA Championship with a six-game NBA Finals triumph over the Los Angeles Lakers.\n*Beginning with this season, all NBA broadcasts on [[NBA on ESPN|ESPN]], [[NBA on ABC|ABC]] and [[NBA on TNT|TNT]] include interviews with the head coaches by the courtside reporter prior to the second and fourth quarter of games. The visiting team's coach is interviewed before the second, the host team's coach is interviewed before the fourth quarter.{{citation needed|date=January 2011}}\n\n===Coaching changes===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"3\"|Offseason\n|-\n! Team\n! 2006\u201307 coach\n! 2007\u201308 coach\n|-\n| [[Charlotte Bobcats]]\n| [[Bernie Bickerstaff]]\n| [[Sam Vincent (basketball)|Sam Vincent]]\n|-\n| [[Houston Rockets]]\n| [[Jeff Van Gundy]]\n| [[Rick Adelman]]\n|-\n| [[Indiana Pacers]]\n| [[Rick Carlisle]]\n| [[Jim O'Brien (basketball, born 1952)|Jim O'Brien]]\n|-\n| [[Memphis Grizzlies]]\n| [[Tony Barone]]\n| [[Marc Iavaroni]]\n|-\n| [[Orlando Magic]]\n| [[Brian Hill (basketball coach)|Brian Hill]]\n| [[Stan Van Gundy]]\n|-\n| [[Sacramento Kings]]\n| [[Eric Musselman]]\n| [[Reggie Theus]]\n|-\n| [[Seattle SuperSonics]]\n| [[Bob Hill]]\n| [[P.J. Carlesimo]]\n|-\n! colspan=\"3\"|In-season\n|-\n! Team\n! Outgoing coach\n! Incoming coach\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|[[Chicago Bulls]]\n| [[Scott Skiles]]\n| [[Pete Myers]]\n|-\n| [[Pete Myers]]\n| [[Jim Boylan]]\n|}\n\n== Final standings ==\n\n===By division===\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n;[[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]]\n# {{2007\u201308 NBA Atlantic standings}}\n# {{2007\u201308 NBA Central standings}}\n# {{2007\u201308 NBA Southeast standings}}\n{{col-2}}\n;[[Western Conference (NBA)|Western Conference]]\n# {{2007\u201308 NBA Northwest standings}}\n# {{2007\u201308 NBA Pacific standings}}\n# {{2007\u201308 NBA Southwest standings}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n===By conference===\n\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n{{2007\u201308 NBA East standings|tiebreakers=yes}}\n{{col-2}}\n{{2007\u201308 NBA West standings|tiebreakers=yes}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n'''Notes'''\n*'''z'''&nbsp;\u2013 Clinched home court advantage for the entire playoffs\n*'''c'''&nbsp;\u2013 Clinched home court advantage for the conference playoffs\n*'''x'''&nbsp;\u2013 Clinched playoff spot\n*'''y'''&nbsp;\u2013 Clinched division title\n*'''w'''&nbsp;\u2013 Clinched NBA 2008 title\n*'''r'''&nbsp;\u2013 Clinched NBA 2008 runners up title\n\n==Playoffs==\nTeams in bold advanced to the next round. The numbers to the left of each team indicate the team's seeding in its conference, and the numbers to the right indicate the number of games the team won in that round. The division champions are marked by an asterisk. [[Home court advantage]] does not necessarily belong to the higher-seeded team, but instead the team with the better regular season record; teams enjoying the home advantage are shown in italics.\n\n{{Main|2008 NBA Playoffs}}\n{{2008 NBA Playoffs}}\n\n==Statistics leaders==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ \n|- \n! Category !! Player || Team || Stat\n|-\n| [[Point (basketball)|Points]] per game || [[LeBron James]] || [[Cleveland Cavaliers]] || 30.0\n|-\n| [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]] per game || [[Dwight Howard]] || [[Orlando Magic]] || 14.2\n|-\n| [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]] per game || [[Chris Paul]] || [[New Orleans Hornets]] || 11.6\n|-\n| [[Steal (basketball)|Steals]] per game || Chris Paul || New Orleans Hornets || 2.71\n|-\n| [[Block (basketball)|Blocks]] per game || [[Marcus Camby]]  || [[Denver Nuggets]]  || 3.61\n|-\n| [[Field goal (basketball)|Field goal]] percentage || [[Andris Biedri\u0146\u0161]] || [[Golden State Warriors]] || .626\n|-\n| [[Free throw]] percentage || [[Peja Stojakovi\u0107]] || New Orleans Hornets || .929\n|-\n| [[Three-point field goal]] percentage || [[Jason Kapono]] || [[Toronto Raptors]] || .483\n|-\n|}\n\n==NBA awards==\n\n===Yearly awards===\n*'''[[NBA Most Valuable Player|Most Valuable Player]]:''' [[Kobe Bryant]], [[Los Angeles Lakers]]<ref>[http://www.nba.com//news/kobe_mvp_080506.html Kobe Bryant Wins Most Valuable Player Award] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100901171948/http://www.nba.com/news/kobe_mvp_080506.html |date=2010-09-01 }}, ''[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]'', May 6, 2008, accessed May 6, 2008.</ref>\n*'''[[NBA Rookie of the Year|Rookie of the Year]]:''' [[Kevin Durant]], [[Seattle SuperSonics]]<ref>[http://www.nba.com//nbatvaffiliates/durant_roy_080501.html Kevin Durant Named Rookie of the Year] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121105024138/http://www.nba.com//nbatvaffiliates/durant_roy_080501.html |date=2012-11-05 }}, ''[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]'', May 1, 2008, accessed May 1, 2008.</ref>\n*'''[[NBA Defensive Player of the Year|Defensive Player of the Year]]:''' [[Kevin Garnett]], [[Boston Celtics]]<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/garnett_defensive_080422.html Kevin Garnett Wins Kia Defensive Player of the Year] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/65arS45Kh?url=http://www.nba.com/news/garnett_defensive_080422.html |date=2012-02-20 }}, ''[[National Basketball Association|NBA]]'', April 22, 2008, accessed April 22, 2008.</ref>\n*'''[[NBA Sixth Man of the Year|Sixth Man of the Year]]:''' [[Manu Gin\u00f3bili]], [[San Antonio Spurs]]<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/sixthman_080421.html Ginobili Wins 2007-08 Sixth Man of the Year Award Presented by Kia Motors] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/6HjcMnQFd?url=http://www.nba.com/news/sixthman_080421.html |date=2013-06-29 }}, ''NBA'', April 21, 2008, accessed April 21, 2008.</ref>\n*'''[[NBA Most Improved Player|Most Improved Player]]:''' [[Hedo T\u00fcrko\u011flu]], [[Orlando Magic]]<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/hedo_mip_080428.html Hedo Turkoglu Wins Most Improved Player Award] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429090922/http://www.nba.com/news/hedo_mip_080428.html |date=2011-04-29 }}, ''NBA'', April 28, 2008, accessed April 28, 2008.</ref>\n*'''[[NBA Coach of the Year|Coach of the Year]]:''' [[Byron Scott (basketball)|Byron Scott]], [[New Orleans Hornets]]<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/scott_coy_080428.html Byron Scott wins 2007-08 NBA Coach of the Year award] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101118221842/http://www.nba.com/news/scott_coy_080428.html |date=2010-11-18 }}, ''NBA'', April 29, 2008, accessed April 29, 2008.</ref>\n*'''[[NBA Executive of the Year Award|Executive of the Year]]:''' [[Danny Ainge]], Boston Celtics<ref>[http://www.nba.com//ainge_executive_080514.html Boston\u2019s Danny Ainge Named 2007-08 NBA Executive of the Year] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101223072700/http://www.nba.com/ainge_executive_080514.html |date=2010-12-23 }}, ''NBA'', May 14, 2008, accessed May 14, 2008.</ref>\n*'''[[NBA Sportsmanship Award|Sportsmanship Award]]:''' [[Grant Hill]], [[Phoenix Suns]]<ref>[http://www.nba.com/news/hill_sportsmanship_080425.html Suns\u2019 Hill Wins 2007-08 NBA Sportsmanship Award] {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/66VlvXEdU?url=http://www.nba.com/news/hill_sportsmanship_080425.html |date=2012-03-28 }}, ''NBA'', April 25, 2008, accessed April 25, 2008.</ref>\n{{col-start}}{{col-3}}\n*'''[[All-NBA First Team]]:'''\n**F [[Kevin Garnett]] \u2013 [[Boston Celtics]]\n**F [[LeBron James]] \u2013 [[Cleveland Cavaliers]]\n**C [[Dwight Howard]] \u2013 [[Orlando Magic]]\n**G [[Kobe Bryant]] \u2013 [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n**G [[Chris Paul]] \u2013 [[New Orleans Hornets]]<ref name=\"allnbateam\">[http://www.nba.com/news/all_nba_080508.html MVP Kobe Bryant highlights All-NBA First team] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111211112818/http://www.nba.com/news/all_nba_080508.html |date=2011-12-11 }}, ''NBA'', May 8, 2008, accessed May 8, 2008.</ref>\n*'''[[NBA All-Defensive First Team]]:'''\n**F [[Kevin Garnett]] \u2013 [[Boston Celtics]]\n**F [[Tim Duncan]] \u2013 [[San Antonio Spurs]]\n**C [[Marcus Camby]] \u2013 [[Denver Nuggets]]\n**G [[Kobe Bryant]] \u2013 [[Los Angeles Lakers]]\n**G [[Bruce Bowen]] \u2013 [[San Antonio Spurs]]<ref name=\"nbadefensiveteam\">[http://www.nba.com/news/defensive_team_080512.html Kobe, Garnett Headline All-Defensive Team] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100726070624/http://www.nba.com/news/defensive_team_080512.html |date=2010-07-26 }}, ''NBA'', May 12, 2008, accessed May 12, 2008.</ref>\n*'''[[NBA All-Rookie First Team]]:'''\n** [[Al Horford]] \u2013 [[Atlanta Hawks]]\n** [[Kevin Durant]] \u2013 [[Seattle SuperSonics]]\n** [[Luis Scola]] \u2013 [[Houston Rockets]]\n** [[Al Thornton]] \u2013 [[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n** [[Jeff Green (basketball)|Jeff Green]