{"title_page": "V\u00e9ronique Besse", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=July 2010}}\n{{Expand French|topic=gov|date=December 2008|V\u00e9ronique Besse}}\n\n'''V\u00e9ronique Besse''' (born 11 August 1963 in [[La Roche-sur-Yon]], [[Vend\u00e9e]]) is a member of the [[National Assembly of France]] and represents the [[Vend\u00e9e]] department.<ref name=\"anfr\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/13/tribun/fiches_id/309643.asp |title=V\u00e9ronique Besse |author=Office of the Secretary General |language=French |year=2012 |publisher=[[National Assembly of France]] |work=Assemblee-nationale.fr |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> She is the current mayor of [[Les Herbiers]], after being elected for the first time in 2014 with 57,76% of votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://veroniquebesse.fr/portrait/|title=Portrait|website=V\u00e9ronique Besse|language=fr-FR|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> She has been reelected at her position for a second time in 2020 with 67,18% of votes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ouest-france.fr/elections/municipales/veronique-besse-reelue-maire-des-herbiers-6781776|title=Municipales en Vend\u00e9e. V\u00e9ronique Besse r\u00e9\u00e9lue maire des Herbiers|last=HUTIN|first=Jeanne|date=2020-03-16|website=Ouest-France.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref> Besse is a member of the [[Movement for France]] and does not align herself with any parliamentary group.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Besse, Veronique}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from La Roche-sur-Yon]]\n[[Category:Movement for France politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (France)]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 13th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 14th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n\n\n{{France-politician-MPF-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=July 2010}}\n{{Expand French|topic=gov|date=December 2008|V\u00e9ronique Besse}}\n\n'''V\u00e9ronique Besse''' (born 11 August 1963 in [[La Roche-sur-Yon]], [[Vend\u00e9e]]) is a member of the [[National Assembly of France]] and represents the [[Vend\u00e9e]] department.<ref name=\"anfr\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.assemblee-nationale.fr/13/tribun/fiches_id/309643.asp |title=V\u00e9ronique Besse |author=Office of the Secretary General |language=French |year=2012 |publisher=[[National Assembly of France]] |work=Assemblee-nationale.fr |accessdate=2 March 2012 }}</ref> Besse is a member of the [[Movement for France]] and does not align herself with any parliamentary group.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Besse, Veronique}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from La Roche-sur-Yon]]\n[[Category:Movement for France politicians]]\n[[Category:Women members of the National Assembly (France)]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 13th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:Deputies of the 14th National Assembly of the French Fifth Republic]]\n[[Category:21st-century French women politicians]]\n\n\n{{France-politician-MPF-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Maela Jeanne Bobinet", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add information concerning her poltical career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/V%C3%A9ronique_Besse"}
{"title_page": "Artur Duarte de Oliveira", "text_new": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name        = Artur Oliveira\n| fullname    = Artur Duarte de Oliveira\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1969|12|27|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Rio Branco, Acre|Rio Branco]], Brazil\n| height      = 1.74 m\n| position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| currentclub = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]] (coach)\n| clubnumber  =\n| years1 = 1989\u20131990 | clubs1 = [[Rio Branco Football Club|Rio Branco-AC]]\n| years2 = 1991      | clubs2 = [[Independ\u00eancia Futebol Clube|Independ\u00eancia]]\n| years3 = 1991\u20131992 | clubs3 = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]]\n| years4 = 1992\u20131996 | clubs4 = [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista]]\n| years5 = 1996\u20131999 | clubs5 = [[FC Porto|Porto]] | caps5 = 64 | goals5 = 11\n| years6 = 1999\u20132001 | clubs6 = [[Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria|Vit\u00f3ria]] | caps6 = 22 | goals6 = 9\n| years7 = 2001      | clubs7 = [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]] | caps7 = 11 | goals7 = 3\n| years8 = 2002\u20132003 | clubs8 = [[Figueirense Futebol Clube|Figueirense]] | caps8 = | goals8 =\n| years9 = 2004      | clubs9 = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]] | caps9 = | goals9 =\n| manageryears1  = 2007      | managerclubs1  = [[Rio Branco Football Club|Rio Branco]]\n| manageryears2  = 2007      | managerclubs2  = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]]\n| manageryears3  = 2008      | managerclubs3  = [[Clube Municipal Ananindeua|Ananindeua]]\n| manageryears4  = 2008      | managerclubs4  = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]]\n| manageryears5  = 2008      | managerclubs5  = [[Castanhal Esporte Clube|Castanhal]]\n| manageryears6  = 2009      | managerclubs6  = [[S\u00e3o Raimundo Esporte Clube (PA)|S\u00e3o Raimundo-PA]]\n| manageryears7  = 2010      | managerclubs7  = [[Camet\u00e1 Sport Club|Camet\u00e1]]\n| manageryears8  = 2011      | managerclubs8  = [[Atl\u00e9tico Acreano]]\n| manageryears9  = 2011\u20132012 | managerclubs9  = [[Galvez Esporte Clube|Galvez]]\n| manageryears10 = 2013      | managerclubs10 = [[Rio Branco Football Club|Rio Branco-AC]]\n| manageryears11 = 2015      | managerclubs11 = [[Galvez Esporte Clube|Galvez]]\n| manageryears12 = 2016      | managerclubs12 = [[Rio Branco Football Club|Rio Branco-AC]]\n| manageryears13 = 2017\u20132018 | managerclubs13 = [[Bragantino Clube do Par\u00e1|Bragantino do Par\u00e1]]\n| manageryears14 = 2018\u2013     | managerclubs14 = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]]\n}}\n'''Artur Duarte de Oliveira''' (born 27 December 1969), simply known as '''Artur''', is a Brazilian former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]], and a current [[Manager (association football)|manager]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Rio Branco, Acre|Rio Branco]], [[Acre (state)|Acre]], Artur spent the vast majority of his career in Portugal after starting out professionally at [[Clube do Remo]]. He signed in 1992 with [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista FC]], scoring 13 times in 25 games in [[1992\u201393 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|his first season]] to help his team to the fourth place.\n\nIn the 1996 summer, after 29 league goals in his last two years combined, Artur moved to [[Porto]] neighbours [[FC Porto]], going on to win six major titles during his three-year spell, including three [[Primeira Liga]] championships in a row. On 18 September 1996 he was one of five players to find the net in a 5\u20130 away win against [[S.L. Benfica]], with the [[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|domestic Supercup]] being conquered [[1996 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|6\u20130 on aggregate]].\n\nArtur returned to his homeland in early 1999, going on to make his [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|S\u00e9rie A]] debuts at nearly 30 with [[Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria]]. He retired five years later, with his first club Remo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.futeboldonorte.com/noticias_materia.php?id=69686|title=Artur Oliveira conta sua hist\u00f3ria no futebol|trans-title=Artur Oliveira tells his story in football|publisher=Futebol do Norte|language=pt|date=10 January 2014|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\nArtur started working as a manager in 2007, with [[Rio Branco Football Club]], to where he returned six years after on 20 August.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ebc.com.br/esportes/serie-c/2013/08/tecnico-everton-goiano-deixa-rio-branco-e-clube-acerta-com-artur-de|title=T\u00e9cnico Everton Goiano deixa Rio Branco e clube acerta com Artur de Oliveira|trans-title=Coach Everton Goiano leaves Rio Branco and club agrees with Artur de Oliveira|publisher=EBC|language=Portuguese|date=20 August 2013|accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref> He was sacked only one month later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://futeboldonorte.com/noticias_materia.php?id=67192|title=Rio Branco dispensa Artur Oliveira e efetiva Tangar\u00e1|trans-title=Rio Branco releases Artur Oliveira and officializes Tangar\u00e1|publisher=Futebol do Norte|language=pt|date=13 September 2013|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n'''Vit\u00f3ria'''\n*[[Copa do Nordeste]]: 1999; Runner-up 2000\n*[[Campeonato Baiano]]: 1999, 2000\n\n'''Figueirense'''\n*[[Campeonato Catarinense]]: 2002\n\n'''Remo'''\n*[[Campeonato Paraense]]: 1991, 1992, 1993, 2004\n\n'''Boavista'''\n*[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]: 1992\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]: Runner-up 1992\u201393\n\n'''Porto'''\n*[[Primeira Liga]]: [[1996\u201397 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1997\u201398]], [[1998\u201399 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1998\u201399]]\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]: [[1997\u201398 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|1997\u201398]]\n*[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]: [[1996 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|1996]], [[1998 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|1998]], Runner-up [[1997 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|1997]]\n\n===Manager===\n'''Rio Branco'''\n*[[Campeonato Acriano]]: 2007\n\n'''Remo'''\n*[[Campeonato Paraense]]: 2008\n\n'''S\u00e3o Raimundo-PA'''\n*[[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie D]]: [[2009 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie D|2009]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo|name=Artur}}\n\n{{Clube do Remo managers}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Brazil|Association football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Artur Duarte De Oliveira}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Rio Branco]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A players]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie B players]]\n[[Category:Rio Branco Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Clube do Remo players]]\n[[Category:Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria players]]\n[[Category:Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas players]]\n[[Category:Figueirense FC players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Boavista F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Porto players]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Brazilian football managers]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie C managers]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie D managers]]\n[[Category:Rio Branco Football Club managers]]\n[[Category:Clube do Remo managers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Brazilian footballer}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n | name        = Artur Oliveira\n | fullname    = Artur Duarte de Oliveira\n | birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1969|12|27|df=y}}\n | birth_place = [[Rio Branco, Acre|Rio Branco]], Brazil\n | height      = {{height|m=1.74|precision=0}}\n | position    = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n | currentclub = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]] (coach)\n | clubnumber  =\n | years1 = 1989\u20131990 | clubs1 = [[Rio Branco Football Club|Rio Branco-AC]]\n | years2 = 1991      | clubs2 = [[Independ\u00eancia Futebol Clube|Independ\u00eancia]]\n | years3 = 1991\u20131992 | clubs3 = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]]\n | years4 = 1992\u20131996 | clubs4 = [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista]]\n | years5 = 1996\u20131999 | clubs5 = [[FC Porto|Porto]] | caps5 = 64 | goals5 = 11\n | years6 = 1999\u20132001 | clubs6 = [[Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria|Vit\u00f3ria]] | caps6 = 22 | goals6 = 9\n | years7 = 2001      | clubs7 = [[Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas|Botafogo]] | caps7 = 11 | goals7 = 3\n | years8 = 2002\u20132003 | clubs8 = [[Figueirense Futebol Clube|Figueirense]] | caps8 = | goals8 =\n | years9 = 2004      | clubs9 = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]] | caps9 = | goals9 =\n  | manageryears1 = 2007      | managerclubs1  = [[Rio Branco Football Club|Rio Branco]]\n | manageryears2  = 2007      | managerclubs2  = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]]\n | manageryears3  = 2008      | managerclubs3  = [[Clube Municipal Ananindeua|Ananindeua]]\n | manageryears4  = 2008      | managerclubs4  = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]]\n | manageryears5  = 2008      | managerclubs5  = [[Castanhal Esporte Clube|Castanhal]]\n | manageryears6  = 2009      | managerclubs6  = [[S\u00e3o Raimundo Esporte Clube (PA)|S\u00e3o Raimundo-PA]]\n | manageryears7  = 2010      | managerclubs7  = [[Camet\u00e1 Sport Club|Camet\u00e1]]\n | manageryears8  = 2011      | managerclubs8  = [[Atl\u00e9tico Acreano]]\n | manageryears9  = 2011\u20132012 | managerclubs9  = [[Galvez Esporte Clube|Galvez]]\n | manageryears10 = 2013      | managerclubs10 = [[Rio Branco Football Club|Rio Branco-AC]]\n | manageryears11 = 2015      | managerclubs11 = [[Galvez Esporte Clube|Galvez]]\n | manageryears12 = 2016      | managerclubs12 = [[Rio Branco Football Club|Rio Branco-AC]]\n | manageryears13 = 2017\u20132018 | managerclubs13 = [[Bragantino Clube do Par\u00e1|Bragantino do Par\u00e1]]\n | manageryears14 = 2018\u2013     | managerclubs14 = [[Clube do Remo|Remo]]\n | club-update =\n | nationalteam-update =\n}}\n'''Artur Duarte de Oliveira''' (born 27 December 1969), simply known as '''Artur''', is a [[Brazil]]ian retired [[Association football|footballer]] who played as a [[Forward (association football)|forward]], and a current [[Manager (association football)|manager]].\n\n==Playing career==\nBorn in [[Rio Branco, Acre|Rio Branco]], [[Acre (state)|Acre]], Artur spent the vast majority of his career in Portugal after starting out professionally at [[Clube do Remo]]. He signed in 1992 with [[Boavista F.C.|Boavista FC]], scoring 13 times in 25 games in [[1992\u201393 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|his first season]] to help his team to the fourth place.\n\nIn the 1996 summer, after 29 league goals in his last two years combined, Artur moved to [[Porto]] neighbours [[FC Porto]], going on to win six major titles during his three-year spell, including three [[Primeira Liga]] championships in a row. On 18 September 1996 he was one of five players to find the net in a 5\u20130 away win against [[S.L. Benfica]], with the [[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|domestic Supercup]] being conquered [[1996 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|6\u20130 on aggregate]].\n\nArtur returned to his homeland in early 1999, going on to make his [[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A|S\u00e9rie A]] debuts at nearly 30 with [[Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria]]. He retired five years later, with his first club Remo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.futeboldonorte.com/noticias_materia.php?id=69686|title=Artur Oliveira conta sua hist\u00f3ria no futebol|trans-title=Artur Oliveira tells his story in football|publisher=Futebol do Norte|language=pt|date=10 January 2014|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Managerial career==\nArtur started working as a manager in 2007, with [[Rio Branco Football Club]], to where he returned six years after on 20 August.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ebc.com.br/esportes/serie-c/2013/08/tecnico-everton-goiano-deixa-rio-branco-e-clube-acerta-com-artur-de|title=T\u00e9cnico Everton Goiano deixa Rio Branco e clube acerta com Artur de Oliveira|trans-title=Coach Everton Goiano leaves Rio Branco and club agrees with Artur de Oliveira|publisher=EBC|language=Portuguese|date=20 August 2013|accessdate=29 September 2013}}</ref> He was sacked only one month later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://futeboldonorte.com/noticias_materia.php?id=67192|title=Rio Branco dispensa Artur Oliveira e efetiva Tangar\u00e1|trans-title=Rio Branco releases Artur Oliveira and officializes Tangar\u00e1|publisher=Futebol do Norte|language=pt|date=13 September 2013|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Honours==\n===Player===\n;Vit\u00f3ria\n*[[Copa do Nordeste]]: 1999; Runner-up 2000\n*[[Campeonato Baiano]]: 1999, 2000\n\n;Figueirense\n*[[Campeonato Catarinense]]: 2002\n\n;Remo\n*[[Campeonato Paraense]]: 1991, 1992, 1993, 2004\n\n;Boavista\n*[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]: 1992\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]: Runner-up 1992\u201393\n\n;Porto\n*[[Primeira Liga]]: [[1996\u201397 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1996\u201397]], [[1997\u201398 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1997\u201398]], [[1998\u201399 Primeira Divis\u00e3o|1998\u201399]]\n*[[Ta\u00e7a de Portugal]]: [[1997\u201398 Ta\u00e7a de Portugal|1997\u201398]]\n*[[Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira]]: [[1996 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|1996]], [[1998 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|1998]], Runner-up [[1997 Superta\u00e7a C\u00e2ndido de Oliveira|1997]]\n\n===Manager===\n;Rio Branco\n*[[Campeonato Acriano]]: 2007\n\n;Remo\n*[[Campeonato Paraense]]: 2008\n\n;S\u00e3o Raimundo-PA\n*[[Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie D]]: [[2009 Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie D|2009]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{ForaDeJogo|name=Artur}}\n\n{{Clube do Remo managers}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Brazil|Association football}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Artur Duarte De Oliveira}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Rio Branco]]\n[[Category:Brazilian footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football forwards]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie A players]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie B players]]\n[[Category:Rio Branco Football Club players]]\n[[Category:Clube do Remo players]]\n[[Category:Esporte Clube Vit\u00f3ria players]]\n[[Category:Botafogo de Futebol e Regatas players]]\n[[Category:Figueirense FC players]]\n[[Category:Primeira Liga players]]\n[[Category:Boavista F.C. players]]\n[[Category:FC Porto players]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate footballers]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Brazilian expatriate sportspeople in Portugal]]\n[[Category:Brazilian football managers]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie C managers]]\n[[Category:Campeonato Brasileiro S\u00e9rie D managers]]\n[[Category:Rio Branco Football Club managers]]\n[[Category:Clube do Remo managers]]\n", "name_user": "Robby.is.on", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor corrections.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artur_Duarte_de_Oliveira"}
{"title_page": "The Domestic Crusaders", "text_new": "{{about|the Off Broadway play by Wajahat Ali on a Pakistani-American Muslim family in post-9/11 America }}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox play\n| name       = The Domestic Crusaders\n| image         = Wajahat Ali The Domestic Crusaders.png\n| caption    =McSweeney's cover of The Domestic Crusaders\n| writer     = [[Wajahat Ali]]\n| genre      = Drama\n| setting    = Post-9/11; family house in the United States\n| subject    = Trials and tribulations of Pakistani-American Muslim family post-9/11\n| premiere   = 2005\n|| place     = Berkeley Repertory Theatre <br>[[Berkeley, California]] \n| orig_lang  = English\n}}\n\n'''''The Domestic Crusaders''''' is a play by [[Wajahat Ali]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newplayexchange.org/users/17805/wajahat-ali|title=wajahat ali {{!}} New Play Exchange|website=newplayexchange.org|language=en|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>about a Pakistani-American Muslim family<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrmea.org/011-april/music-arts-the-domestic-crusaders-book-launch-in-washington-d.html|title=Music & Arts:|website=WRMEA|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/09/theater/09domestic.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=wajahat&st=cse|title=A Pakistani-American Family Is Caught in Some Cultural Cross-Fire|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Laurie|last=Goodstein|date=September 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe play made its [[Off-Broadway]] premiere at the [[Nuyorican Poets Caf\u00e9]] on September 11, 2009. The story is about the lives of a Pakistani-American family grappling with their own internal trials and tribulations, the changing dynamics of American society and a globalized, post-[[9/11]] world.<ref>[http://www.beliefnet.com/Faiths/Islam/2009/03/Crusading-for-Modern-Islamic-Art.aspx \"Crusading for Modern Islamic Art\"], Beliefnet.com, March 2009.</ref> [[McSweeney's]] published the play in the Fall of 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcsweeneys.net/pages/download-wajahat-alis-the-domestic-crusaders|title=Download Wajahat Ali\u2019s The Domestic Crusaders - McSweeney\u2019s Internet Tendency|website=McSweeney's Internet Tendency|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\n==Summary==\nThe play takes place over the course of one day during the present time, in an upper-middle-class suburban family home of a Muslim-American family of Pakistani origins.<ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\nWith a keen sense of timing, this dramatic-comedy utilizes the generational and culture-driven political and social evolution of American society following 9/11<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kennedy-center.org/Artist/A66901|title=Wajahat Ali|website=www.kennedy-center.org|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>. Six members of a Pakistani-American Muslim family, spanning three generations, reunite at the family home to celebrate the youngest son's 21st birthday.  Each individual family member, or \"domestic crusader\", attempts to assert his or her individual definition of self and destiny in the face of collective family and societal constraints, fears and misunderstandings.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/wajahat-ali/the-domestic-crusaders-ma_b_277216.html|title='The Domestic Crusaders': Making History With Muslim American Theater|last=Ali|first=Wajahat|date=2009-10-20|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\n*'''Hakim''' is the grandfather, a retired, Pakistani army officer\n*'''Salman''' is the father who oscillates between prideful exuberance and the daily grind that preys on his feelings of self-worth\n*'''Khulsoom''' is Salman's wife who misses her native land and struggles to impart her traditional values onto her American-raised children\n*'''Salahuddin''' is the eldest son who is a successful businessman\n*'''Fatima''' is the middle child and a social justice activist\n*'''Ghafur''' is the youngest child\n\n==History==\nAli, who is an attorney and writer in the [[Bay Area]], began writing the play in 2001 while studying at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. The idea for the play came from Ali's writing professor, [[Ishmael Reed]], who encouraged him to write a theatrical piece that shed light on the inner lives<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/14568670-the-domestic-crusaders|title=The Domestic Crusaders|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> of American Muslims, an increasingly marginalized American religious community.<ref name=\"NYT\"/>\n\nIn 2004, the play established its \"grassroots/seat of the pants\" mode of operation with a series of staged readings launched at the Mehran Restaurant in Newark, California, and continued with Oakland Public Library sponsored events.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAli explained his choice of the play's ironic title in the February 2011 issue of ''[[American Theatre (magazine)|American Theatre]]'', saying it refers to \"hundreds of years of alleged inherent acrimony between the West and Islam....I wanted to reframe that within this multi-hyphenated Muslim-American family. These 'crusaders,' instead of being blood-thirsty warmongers, are nuanced, hypocritical, self-involved, quirky people. Instead of Kalashnikovs and swords and missiles, we see them fighting with stinging barbs and wit and regrets and secrets\u2014good old-fashioned drama and melodrama.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Premiere==\nThe two-act play officially premiered as a 2005 showcase production<ref>Bullock, Ken (July 8, 2005), [http://www.berkeleydailyplanet.com/issue/2005-07-08/article/21811?headline=Play-Explores-Post-9-11-Tensions-in-Family-Portrait-By-KEN-BULLOCK-Special-to-the-Planet&status=301 \"Election Section: Play Explores Post-9/11 Tensions in Family Portrait\"], ''Berkeley Daily Planet''.</ref> at the Tony Award-winning [[Berkeley Repertory Theatre]]. The play was and continues to be directed by acclaimed choreographer and director [[Carla Blank]]. Its NYC debut, on September 11, 2009, at the [[Nuyorican Poets Caf\u00e9]] was followed by a sold-out five-week run, which broke attendance records for plays<ref>{{Cite web|last=Boulder NewsTeam|title=The Domestic Crusaders and Q&A with Playwright Wajahat Ali|date=2013-01-11|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pHh94oq5t_c|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> at this landmark [[Off-Broadway]] theater.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2009/09/22/aftermath-and-domestic-crusaders-examine-the-muslim-experience/|title=Aftermath and Domestic Crusaders Examine the Muslim Experience|website=www.villagevoice.com|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>  In his Nuyorican program notes, Ali explained the choice of this date for the play's New York opening:<ref name=\":4\" /> \"I believe by proactively confronting the history of that day through art and dialogue we can finally move beyond the anger, the violence, the extremism, the separatism, the pain and the regret, and build a bridge of understanding and reconciliation.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe play received its international premiere performances at [[MuslimFest]] in [[Mississauga]], [[Ontario]], Canada, on July 31 and August 1, 2010, and was showcased in Washington, D.C.'s Atlas Performing Arts Center on November 12, 2010, and at the [[Kennedy Center]]'s Millennium Hall on November 14, 2010. The one-hour performance of Act One remains archived on the Kennedy Center website.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of cultural references to the September 11 attacks]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/32783056 MSNBC Article about the play]\n*[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21134540 MSNBC Interview by Pat Battle]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090604134907/http://www.domesticcrusaders.com/reviews.html Additional Reviews]\n\n{{Authority Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Domestic Crusaders}}\n[[Category:Islam in the United States]]\n[[Category:Asian-American plays]]\n[[Category:2005 plays]]\n[[Category:Pakistani-American literature]]\n[[Category:Off-Broadway plays]]\n[[Category:American plays]]\n[[Category:Plays set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Plays about the September 11 attacks]]\n[[Category:Plays about families]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the Off Broadway play by Wajahat Ali on a Pakistani-American Muslim family in post-9/11 America }}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox play\n| name       = The Domestic Crusaders\n| image         = Wajahat Ali The Domestic Crusaders.png\n| caption    =McSweeney's cover of The Domestic Crusaders\n| writer     = [[Wajahat Ali]]\n| genre      = Drama\n| setting    = Post-9/11; family house in the United States\n| subject    = Trials and tribulations of Pakistani-American Muslim family post-9/11\n| premiere   = 2005\n|| place     = Berkeley Repertory Theatre <br>[[Berkeley, California]] \n| orig_lang  = English\n}}\n\n'''''The Domestic Crusaders''''' is a play by [[Wajahat Ali]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://newplayexchange.org/users/17805/wajahat-ali|title=wajahat ali {{!}} New Play Exchange|website=newplayexchange.org|language=en|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>about a Pakistani-American Muslim family<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.wrmea.org/011-april/music-arts-the-domestic-crusaders-book-launch-in-washington-d.html|title=Music & Arts:|website=WRMEA|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/09/09/theater/09domestic.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=wajahat&st=cse|title=A Pakistani-American Family Is Caught in Some Cultural Cross-Fire|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=Laurie|last=Goodstein|date=September 8, 2009}}</ref>\n\nThe play made its [[Off-Broadway]] premiere at the [[Nuyorican Poets Caf\u00e9]] on September 11, 2009. The story is about the lives of a Pakistani-American family grappling with their own internal trials and tribulations, the changing dynamics of American society and a globalized, post-9/11 world.<ref>[http://www.beliefnet.com/Faiths/Islam/2009/03/Crusading-for-Modern-Islamic-Art.aspx \"Crusading for Modern Islamic Art\"], Beliefnet.com, March 2009.</ref> [[McSweeney's]] published the play in the Fall of 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcsweeneys.net/pages/download-wajahat-alis-the-domestic-crusaders|title=Download Wajahat Ali\u2019s The Domestic Crusaders - McSweeney\u2019s Internet Tendency|website=McSweeney's Internet Tendency|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\n==Summary==\nThe play takes place over the course of one day during the present time, in an upper-middle-class suburban family home of a Muslim-American family of Pakistani origins.<ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\nWith a keen sense of timing, this dramatic-comedy utilizes the generational and culture-driven political and social evolution of American society following 9/11<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kennedy-center.org/Artist/A66901|title=Wajahat Ali|website=www.kennedy-center.org|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>. Six members of a Pakistani-American Muslim family, spanning three generations, reunite at the family home to celebrate the youngest son's 21st birthday.  Each individual family member, or \"domestic crusader\", attempts to assert his or her individual definition of self and destiny in the face of collective family and societal constraints, fears and misunderstandings.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/wajahat-ali/the-domestic-crusaders-ma_b_277216.html|title='The Domestic Crusaders': Making History With Muslim American Theater|last=Ali|first=Wajahat|date=2009-10-20|website=HuffPost|language=en|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>\n\n==Characters==\n*'''Hakim''' is the grandfather, a retired, Pakistani army officer\n*'''Salman''' is the father who oscillates between prideful exuberance and the daily grind that preys on his feelings of self-worth\n*'''Khulsoom''' is Salman's wife who misses her native land and struggles to impart her traditional values onto her American-raised children\n*'''Salahuddin''' is the eldest son who is a successful businessman\n*'''Fatima''' is the middle child and a social justice activist\n*'''Ghafur''' is the youngest child\n\n==History==\nAli, who is an attorney and writer in the [[Bay Area]], began writing the play in 2001 while studying at the [[University of California, Berkeley]]. The idea for the play came from Ali's writing professor, [[Ishmael Reed]], who encouraged him to write a theatrical piece that shed light on the inner lives<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.goodreads.com/work/best_book/14568670-the-domestic-crusaders|title=The Domestic Crusaders|website=www.goodreads.com|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> of American Muslims, an increasingly marginalized American religious community.<ref name=\"NYT\"/>\n\nIn 2004, the play established its \"grassroots/seat of the pants\" mode of operation with a series of staged readings launched at the Mehran Restaurant in Newark, California, and continued with Oakland Public Library sponsored events.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAli explained his choice of the play's ironic title in the February 2011 issue of ''[[American Theatre (magazine)|American Theatre]]'', saying it refers to \"hundreds of years of alleged inherent acrimony between the West and Islam....I wanted to reframe that within this multi-hyphenated Muslim-American family. These 'crusaders,' instead of being blood-thirsty warmongers, are nuanced, hypocritical, self-involved, quirky people. Instead of Kalashnikovs and swords and missiles, we see them fighting with stinging barbs and wit and regrets and secrets\u2014good old-fashioned drama and melodrama.\"<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n==Premiere==\nThe two-act play officially premiered as a 2005 showcase production<ref>Bullock, Ken (July 8, 2005), [http://www.berkeleydailyplanet.com/issue/2005-07-08/article/21811?headline=Play-Explores-Post-9-11-Tensions-in-Family-Portrait-By-KEN-BULLOCK-Special-to-the-Planet&status=301 \"Election Section: Play Explores Post-9/11 Tensions in Family Portrait\"], ''Berkeley Daily Planet''.</ref> at the Tony Award-winning [[Berkeley Repertory Theatre]]. The play was and continues to be directed by acclaimed choreographer and director [[Carla Blank]]. Its NYC debut, on September 11, 2009, at the [[Nuyorican Poets Caf\u00e9]] was followed by a sold-out five-week run, which broke attendance records for plays<ref>{{Cite web|last=Boulder NewsTeam|title=The Domestic Crusaders and Q&A with Playwright Wajahat Ali|date=2013-01-11|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pHh94oq5t_c|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref> at this landmark [[Off-Broadway]] theater.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.villagevoice.com/2009/09/22/aftermath-and-domestic-crusaders-examine-the-muslim-experience/|title=Aftermath and Domestic Crusaders Examine the Muslim Experience|website=www.villagevoice.com|access-date=2019-05-13}}</ref>  In his Nuyorican program notes, Ali explained the choice of this date for the play's New York opening:<ref name=\":4\" /> \"I believe by proactively confronting the history of that day through art and dialogue we can finally move beyond the anger, the violence, the extremism, the separatism, the pain and the regret, and build a bridge of understanding and reconciliation.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe play received its international premiere performances at [[MuslimFest]] in [[Mississauga]], [[Ontario]], Canada, on July 31 and August 1, 2010, and was showcased in Washington, D.C.'s Atlas Performing Arts Center on November 12, 2010, and at the [[Kennedy Center]]'s Millennium Hall on November 14, 2010. The one-hour performance of Act One remains archived on the Kennedy Center website.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of cultural references to the September 11 attacks]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/32783056 MSNBC Article about the play]\n*[http://www.nbcnews.com/id/21134540 MSNBC Interview by Pat Battle]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090604134907/http://www.domesticcrusaders.com/reviews.html Additional Reviews]\n\n{{Authority Control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Domestic Crusaders}}\n[[Category:Islam in the United States]]\n[[Category:Asian-American plays]]\n[[Category:2005 plays]]\n[[Category:Pakistani-American literature]]\n[[Category:Off-Broadway plays]]\n[[Category:American plays]]\n[[Category:Plays set in the United States]]\n[[Category:Plays about the September 11 attacks]]\n[[Category:Plays about families]]\n", "name_user": "Proscribe", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:w/link added", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Domestic_Crusaders"}
{"title_page": "Michael McMillan", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Michael McMillan\n| image         =\n| alt           = \n| caption       = McMillan at the British Library, February 2016\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    =  {{birth year and age|1962}} <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people -->\n| birth_place   = [[High Wycombe]], [[UK]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = British\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Playwright, artist/curator\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = ''The West Indian Front Room''\n}}\n'''Michael McMillan''' (born 1962)<ref>[http://www.uprising-art.com/en/portfolio/michael-mcmillan-st-vincent-uk/ \"Michael McMillan | St. Vincent \u2013 UK], Uprising Art.</ref> is a [[United Kingdom|British]] playwright, artist, curator and educator, born in England to parents who were migrants from [[St Vincent and the Grenadines]] (SVG).<ref name=PP>[http://www.peckhamplatform.com/artists/michael-mcmillan \"Artists: Michael McMillan\"], Peckham Platform.</ref> As an academic, he focuses his research on \"the creative process, ethnography, oral histories, material culture and performativity\".<ref name=Uprising1 /> He is the author of several plays, and as an artist is best known for his first installation, ''The West Indian Front Room'', which was exhibited with great success in 2005, attracting more than 35,000 visitors in its initial outing at the Geffrye Museum, and going on to inspire a [[BBC Four]] documentary called ''Tales from the Front Room'' (2007), a website<ref>[http://www.iniva.org/press/2007/front_room \"Iniva launches the The Front Room website\"], InIVA press release, 15 October 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.thefrontroom.org.uk/ The Front Room] interactive website.</ref> a 2009 book, ''The Front Room: Migrant Aesthetics in the Home'', and various international commissions, such as ''Van Huis Uit: The Living Room of Migrants in the Netherlands'' (Imagine IC, [[Amsterdam]], and Netherlands Tour, 2007\u201308)<ref>Michael McMillan, [http://www.iniva.net/frontroom/media/files/essays/VHU_GuidedTalk.pdf \"Van Huis Uit/That\u2019s the way we do it\u2026!: The Living Room of Migrants in The Netherlands.\"] Guided Talk, April 2007.</ref> and ''A Living Room Surrounded by Salt'' (IBB, [[Cura\u00e7ao]], 2008).<ref name=\"Uprising interview\" /> A more recent installation of the [[Bogle-L'Ouverture Publications#Bookshop|Walter Rodney Bookshop]] featured as part of the 2015 exhibition ''[[No Colour Bar]]'' at the [[Guildhall Art Gallery]].\n\nMcMillan has said of the range of his work: \"I was a painter before I was a playwright/dramatist and through making live art pieces and writing critically about performance, photography, visual arts culture, I have come home in a sense to fine arts, through making mixed-media installations, which given my interest in performativity background can be seen also as theatre sets. My work and practice is often interdisciplinary using mixed media, installations and performance.\"<ref name=\"Uprising interview\" />\n\n==Life and career==\n\nMichael McMillan was born in 1962 in [[High Wycombe]], UK, of [[Caribbean]] migrant heritage;<ref name=\"Uprising interview\" /> as he has said, \"Both my parents came from [[St Vincent & the Grenadines]] and ... were 'arrivants', to use [[Edward Kamau Brathwaite]]'s term, from colonies where they were imbued with English culture.\"<ref name=Wasafiri>[http://www.wasafiri.org/pages/news_01/news_item.asp?News_01ID=263 \"Michael McMillan reviews - Migrations: Journeys into British Art - Tate Britain 31 Jan - 12 Aug 2012\" (biographical note)], ''[[Wasafiri]]'', 7 March 2012.</ref> Given this background, he has said, \"I grew up with learning three languages: the creole spoken by my parents as a fusion of an English lexicon and an African grammar; the [[Jamaican English]] spoken on the streets of [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]] and around London and the London English spoken at school.\"<ref>Michael McMillan, [http://www.ericascourti.com/soundingperformance/michael_mcmillan.html \"Oral Histories in an Ethnographic Context\"], Sounding Performance, November 2007.</ref> He won an essay competition, run by [[Len Garrison]]'s ACER (Afro-Caribbean Education Resource),<ref>[[Mike Phillips (writer)|Mike Phillips]], [https://www.theguardian.com/news/2003/feb/28/guardianobituaries.highereducation \"Obituary: Len Garrison - Recording the history of black Britons for future generations\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 28 February 2003.</ref> and after going to [[FESTAC 77]] (the Second World Festival of African Arts and Culture), he wrote his play ''The School Leaver'' (1978), which was produced at the [[Royal Court Theatre]]'s Young Writers' Festival.<ref name=BPArchive>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/playwrights/mcmillan-michael \"Michael McMillan\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n\nMcMillan read sociology and African and Asian studies at [[Sussex University]], graduating in 1984,<ref name=Uprising1>[http://www.uprising-art.com/en/portfolio/michael-mcmillan-st-vincent-uk/ \"Michael McMillan | St. Vincent \u2013 UK\"], Uprising Art, 12 April 2012.</ref> and then earned an MA degree in Independent Film & Video from [[Central Saint Martins]], London, in 1991.<ref name=enroute>[http://www.arts.ac.uk/media/arts/about-ual/diversity/documents/En-Route-Michael-McMillan.pdf \"CSM Alumnus Michael McMillan\"], en>route, UAL.</ref> From 2000, he was a [[Royal Literary Fund]] Writing Fellow<ref>Fellows: [http://www.rlf.org.uk/fellowships/michael-mcmillan/ \"Michael McMillan, Non-fiction writer, Playwright\"], Royal Literary Fund.</ref> at the [[London College of Communication]] and went on to become, since 2003, a Visiting Professor of Creative Writing at the [[University of the Arts London]] (UAL), and a researcher and Associate Lecturer at the [[London College of Fashion]] (LCF), teaching predominantly Cultural & Historical Studies.<ref name=PP /><ref name=enroute /> He was awarded a practice-based Arts Doctorate from [[Middlesex University]] in 2010.<ref name=iniva>[http://www.iniva.org/library/news/clothes_cloth_and_culture_group_sept_2014 \"Clothes, Cloth and Culture Group: 'Saga Bwoys' and Bedouin Women\"], [[InIVA]], 25 September 2014.</ref><ref>[http://placeinternational.org/mcmillan.htm \"Associate Member, Dr Michael McMillan\"], PLaCE (UK).</ref> In 2010\u201311, he was Arts in Health & Well Being artist-in-residence in [[North Wales]].<ref name=Uprising1 />\n\n===Writing===\n\nMcMillan's interest in oral history and the stories of first-generation Caribbean migrants is reflected in early writings such as ''Brother to Brother'' (1996) and ''The Black Boy Pub & Other Stories'' (1997), which used recordings of interviews done during a year's residence in High Wycombe,<ref>Reva Klein, [https://www.tes.com/article.aspx?storycode=56121 \"No place like home\"], ''TES'', 11 May 2008.</ref> where many of those arriving in particular from SVG had settled.<ref>Michael McMillan, [https://books.google.com/books?id=EQkeAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=%22michael+mcmillan%22+born+st+vincent&source=bl&ots=-w2Ap-8S8p&sig=Z0yBa2iG2qO-PLmZktqx9qUXdOo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBWoVChMI7dm8gqeQyAIVTFgaCh3y6AzC#v=onepage&q=%22michael%20mcmillan%22%20born%20st%20vincent&f=false \"De Mudder Tongue: Oral History Work as an Arts Practice\"], in Matthew Partington and Linda Sandino (eds), ''Oral History in the Visual Arts'', A & C Black, 2013 (pp. 25\u201333), p. 26.</ref><ref>Natricia Duncan, [http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/caribbean-island-changed-uk-town \"The Caribbean Island That Changed A UK Town \u2014 How people from St Vincent and the Grenadines transformed life in High Wycombe\"], ''[[The Voice (British newspaper)|The Voice]]'', 28 July 2013.</ref> As a dramatist, he has had work performed and produced by the [[Royal Court Theatre]], [[Channel 4]], [[BBC Radio 4]], and in venues across the UK.<ref name=PP /><ref name=Doollee>[http://www.doollee.com/PlaywrightsM/mcmillan-michael.html Michael McMillan] at Doollee.com.</ref> His play ''The School Leaver'' was published by the [[Black Ink Collective]] in 1978, when McMillan was 16 years old, and was reprinted several times.<ref>Desrie Thomson-George, [https://www.thebookseller.com/blogs/legacy-black-ink-426351 \"The legacy of Black Ink\"], ''[[The Bookseller]]'', 7 November 2016.</ref> His other plays include ''Master Juba'' (2006), ''Babel Junction'' (2006), and a new translation of [[Bertholt Brecht]]'s ''[[The Good Person of Sezuan]]'',<ref>[http://www.arts.ac.uk/chelsea/events/research/taste-conference/speaker-profiles/ \"Speaker profiles: Dr Michael McMillan\"], UAL.</ref> set in [[Jamaica]] in the 1980s.<ref name=Wasafiri />\n\nMcMillan has written a number of essays and articles in national and international publications, and has presented papers at conferences and symposiums in the UK, Europe, Canada, USA, Caribbean and Brazil, including as keynote speaker at the 2006 \"Islands in Between\" Conference on Language, Literature & History of the Eastern Caribbean ([[University of the West Indies]], School of Continuing Studies, St. Vincent & the Grenadines).<ref name=AfroComb />\n\n===Installations===\nAlongside teaching, McMillan has also worked on mixed-media exhibitions and publications. His first installation, ''The West Indian Front Room'' (he uses \"the term 'West Indian' as it refers to a particular moment of post-[[World War II]] Caribbean migration to England and the wider Diaspora\"),<ref name=\"Uprising interview\">Clelia Coussonnet, [http://blog.uprising-art.com/en/exclusive-interview-michael-mcmillan-2/ \"Exclusive Interview: Michael McMillan \u2013 in the framework of the exhibition Who More Sci-Fi than Us\" (May 2012)], Uprising Art, 2 July 2012.</ref> drew on memories of the domestic setting created by his parents and their like after they migrated to Britain, featuring a recreation of a typical front room of the 1970s to raise  \"questions about the constructions of diaspora, identity, race, class and gender in the domestic interior\".<ref>Michael McMillan, [http://www.mona.uwi.edu/conferences/literatures/ABS/ABS%20McMillan.pdf \"The \u2018West Indian\u2019 Front Room: migrant aesthetics in the home\"], University of the West Indies, Mona.</ref> According to cultural theorist [[Stuart Hall (cultural theorist)|Stuart Hall]], \"The front room is a conservative element of black domestic life, which is more complex and rich than the generality of the society ever realises\"; nevertheless, McMillan recalled in an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'': <blockquote>\"Growing up in our front room caused me much aesthetic distress. The wallpaper and carpet never seemed to match, and Jim Reeves would be crooning from the Blue Spot radiogram on a Sunday. This room was based on the Victorian parlour and was inscribed with a formal code of behaviour because it was reserved for receiving guests. It was packed with furniture, ornaments and soft furnishings surrounded by a gallery of pictures and photographs.\"<ref name=Guardian>Michael McMillan, [https://www.theguardian.com/society/2009/sep/16/african-caribbean-immigration-front-rooms-book \"Home is where the art is \u2014 The front rooms of African-Caribbean immigrants to the UK are centre stage in a new book\"], ''The Guardian'', 16 September 2009.</ref></blockquote> Mounted at London's [[Geffrye Museum]] in October 2005, the critically acclaimed exhibition resonated with more than 35,000 visitors who represented a variety of ages, genders and social, cultural and ethnic backgrounds.<ref name=Guardian /> Different versions have since been remade in other countries and cultural settings, including in the Netherlands and in Cura\u00e7ao, and the associated BBC4 television documentary ''Tales from the Front Room'' was broadcast in 2007. He has also made presentations on ''The Front Room'' at the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] (2009), [[Clark University]], Worcester (2009) and [[Northwestern University]], [[Chicago]], (2008).<ref name=AfroComb>[http://www.originsoftheafrocomb.co.uk/project/committee.html \"The committee\"], Origins of the Afro Comb.</ref> A book entitled ''The Front Room: Migrant Aesthetics in the Home'' followed in 2009.<ref>Michael McMillan, [http://svgblog.blogspot.co.uk/2009/09/life-before-ikea-by-michael-mcmillan.html \"Life before IKEA\"]; via Karl Eklund, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines blog, 7 September 2009.</ref>\n\nAnother installation-based exhibition was ''The Beauty Shop'' (2008) at the [[198 Contemporary Arts and Learning|198 Gallery]] in south London,<ref>[http://www.198.org.uk/artistic-programmes/archives/beauty-shop \"The Beauty Shop\"], Archives, 198 Contemporary Arts & Learning.</ref> where, as with ''The Front Room'', McMillan \"tried to create a tangible sense of performance. Visitors were encouraged to respond to them as theatre as much as art.\"<ref>Michael McMillan, [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/theatreblog/2009/sep/30/black-theatre-plays-roy-williams \"There's more to black theatre than plays\"], ''The Guardian'', 30 September 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he recreated the [[Bogle-L'Ouverture Publications#Bookshop|Walter Rodney Bookshop]] as an installation within the exhibition ''[[No Colour Bar: Black British Art in Action 1960\u20131990]]'' at the [[Guildhall Art Gallery]] (July 2015\u2013January 2016),<ref>William Axtell, [http://www.culture24.org.uk/art/art531290-guildlhall-celebrates-black-british-artists-with-no-colour-bar-black-british-art-in-action-1960-1990 \"Guildhall celebrates black British artists with No Colour Bar: Black British Art in Action\"], Culture24, 9 July 2015.</ref> and participated in related events.<ref>[http://artmaplondon.com/artmap/events/radical-readings-from-the-walter-rodney-bookshop-at-the-guildhall-art-gallery-65728/ \"Radical Readings from the Walter Rodney Bookshop at the Guildhall Art Gallery\"], Art Map London, September 2015.</ref><ref>[http://huntleysonline.com/f-h-a-l-m-a/events/ FHALMA \u2014 Events: \"No Colour Bar: Black British Art in Action 1960 \u2013 1990\"], Huntleys Online.</ref><ref>[http://nocolourbar.blogspot.co.uk/2015/08/personal-insight-from-curator-michael.html \"Personal Insight from Curator Michael McMillan\"], No Colour Bar Blogspot, 24 August 2015.</ref>\n\nAnother recent work is ''Doing Nothing Is Not An Option'', a site-responsive mixed-media installation to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the death of [[Ken Saro-Wiwa]] by exploring the relationship between local people in [[Peckham]] and the memory of the [[Nigeria]]n writer and activist.<ref>[http://www.peckhamplatform.com/system/files/082015/55c1fc7b7d636859840004a9/original/Michael_McMillan_Exhibition_PR_FINAL.pdf?1438776443 \"Doing Nothing Is Not An Option\"], Michael McMillan | Peckham Platform | 17 September \u2013 22 November 2015.</ref><ref>[https://vimeo.com/143785039 \"Doing Nothing Is Not An Option\"], video from Peckham Platform.</ref>\n\n==Selected curatorial work==\n* \"My Hair: Black Hair Culture, Style and Politics\" (in ''Origins of the Afro Comb'', Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, 2013)\n* \"I Miss My Mum\u2019s Cooking\" (in ''Who More Sci-Fi Than Us'', KAdE Kunsthal, [[Amersfoort]], [[Netherlands]], 2012)\n* \"The Waiting Room\" (in ''Stories and Journeys'', [[Gwynedd]] Museum & Art Gallery, [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]], [[North Wales]], 2012)\n* ''The Southall Story'' (South Bank Centre, 2010)\n* ''A Living Room Surrounded by Salt'' (Instituto Buena Bista, [[Cura\u00e7ao]], 2008)\n* ''The Beauty Shop'' (198 Contemporary Arts and Learning, Brixton, 25 January 2008 \u2013 28 March 2013)\n* ''Van Huis Uit: The Living Room of Migrants in the Netherlands'' (Imagine IC, Amsterdam, and Netherlands Tour, 2007\u201308)\n* ''The West Indian Front Room'' (Geffrye Museum, 2005\u201306)<ref>Michael McMillan, [https://www.academia.edu/290317/The_West_Indian_Front_Room_Reflections_on_a_Diasporic_Phenomenon \"The 'West Indian' Front Room: Reflections on a Diasporic Phenomenon\"], ''Small Axe: A Caribbean Journal of Criticism'' (SX 28, Vol. 13, No. 1, March 2009) {{ISSN|0799-0537}}. Abstract, Academia/</ref>\n* \"The Walter Rodney Bookshop\" (in ''No Colour Bar: Black British Art in Action 1960\u20131990'', Guildhall Art Gallery, 10 July 2015 \u2013 24 January 2016)\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''The Waiting Room: An audio-visual tale of an artist in residence at the Alaw Ward (Cancer & Palliative Care Unit) in Ysbyty Gwynedd & Rheumatology Clinics in Ysbyty Gwynedd and Ysbyty Llandudno'' (2006)\n* ''Same Difference: 25 Years of International Youth Volunteering with the Daneford Trust'' (2006).\n* ''Living Proof: Views of a World Living with HIV/AIDS'' (Artist Agency, 1992).\n* ''The Black Boy Pub & Other Stories: The black experience in High Wycombe'' (Wycombe District Council, 1997).\n* ''Growing Up Is Hard To Do: A Book For Young People & Adults About Sexual Health'' (Young People's Health Project, 2000).\n* ''The Front Room: Migrant Aesthetics in the Home'' (Black Dog Publishing, 2009, {{ISBN|978-1906155858}})<ref>Michael McMillan, [https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/1906155852 ''The Front Room'' (2009)] at Amazon.</ref>\n* ''If I Could Fly: An anthology of writings from young men at Orchard Lodge Resource Centre'' (Southwark Social Services, 1998).\n* Editor, ''Words, Sounds & Power Anthology'' (Centerprise Publishing Project, 1988)\n* ''On Duty'' (Akira Press, 1984)<ref name=\"BPArchive\"/>\n*''The School Leaver'' ([[Black Ink Collective]], 1978)<ref name=AfroComb />\n\n==Plays and performance pieces==\n* New translation of ''[[The Good Person of Sezuan]]'' by [[Bertolt Brecht]] (2010 & 2012)<ref name=Doollee />\n* ''Babel Junction'' ([[Hackney Empire|Empire Theatre]], 2006)<ref name=Doollee /><ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/babel-junctions \"Babel Junctions\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''Master Juba'' (Luton Library Theatre, Albany Theatre, 2006)<ref name=Doollee /><ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/master-juba \"Master Juba\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''Can you Play Football?'' (2004)\n* ''Blood for Britain'' (BBC Radio 4 Drama, 2001) \n* ''After Windrush'' ([[Oval House Theatre]], 1998)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/after-windrush \"After Windrush\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''Brother to Brother'' ([[Lyric Hammersmith]] and tour, 1996 & 1998); in Cheryl Robson (ed.), ''Black and Asian Plays Anthology'', Aurora Metro, 2000<ref name=Doollee /><ref>Susan Croft, [http://media.vam.ac.uk/media/documents/legacy_documents/file_upload/37047_file.pdf?q=plays \"Black Playwrights in Britain in Print\" (bibliography)], VAM.</ref><ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/brother-brother \"Brother To Brother\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''I Hope It's Not a Black Man'' (1996)\n* ''Invisible'' (Double Edge Theatre Company; 1993 & 1998)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/invisible \"Invisible\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''The Last Blind Date'' (Artists Alliance/Live Theatre, 1992)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/last-blind-date \"Last Blind Date, The\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''Portrait of a Shopping Centre as a Cathedral'' (1990)\n* ''First Impressions'' (Perspective Theatre Company, 1988)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/first-impressions \"First Impressions\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''On Duty'' (Carlton Centre, Kilburn, 1983)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/duty \"On Duty\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''Carve Your Name'' ([[The Old Vic Theatre]], 1981)\n* ''Day of Action'' (Brent Black People's Theatre, 1981)\n* ''Hard Time Pressure'' ([[Royal Court Theatre]], 1980)\n* ''The School Leaver'' (Royal Court Theatre, 1978)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/school-leaver \"The School Leaver\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.uprising-art.com/en/portfolio/michael-mcmillan-st-vincent-uk/ \"Michael McMillan | St. Vincent \u2013 UK\"], Uprising Art.\n* [http://blog.uprising-art.com/exclusive-interview-michael-mcmillan/ \"Exclusive Interview: Michael McMillan \u2013 in the framework of the exhibition Who More Sci-Fi than Us\"], Uprising Art, 2 July 2012.\n* [http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/playwrights/mcmillan-michael \"Michael McMillan\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.\n* [http://www.doollee.com/PlaywrightsM/mcmillan-michael.html Michael McMillan] at Doollee.com.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TVM6vAEGv64 \"Artist Shiraz Bayjoo In Conversation with Michael McMillan, 5 Feb 2015\"], InivaArts. YouTube.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMillan, Michael}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Black British artists]]\n[[Category:Black British writers]]\n[[Category:Black British academics]]\n[[Category:English people of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines descent]]\n[[Category:British curators]]\n[[Category:English curators]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Sussex]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Central Saint Martins]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of the Arts London]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Michael McMillan\n| image         =\n| alt           = \n| caption       = McMillan at the British Library, February 2016\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    =  {{birth year and age|1962}} <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people -->\n| birth_place   = [[High Wycombe]], [[UK]]\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = British\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = Playwright, artist/curator\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = \n| notable_works = ''The West Indian Front Room''\n}}\n'''Michael McMillan''' (born 1962)<ref>[http://www.uprising-art.com/en/portfolio/michael-mcmillan-st-vincent-uk/ \"Michael McMillan | St. Vincent \u2013 UK], Uprising Art.</ref> is a [[United Kingdom|British]] playwright, artist/curator and educator, born in England to parents who were migrants from [[St Vincent and the Grenadines]] (SVG).<ref name=PP>[http://www.peckhamplatform.com/artists/michael-mcmillan \"Artists: Michael McMillan\"], Peckham Platform.</ref> As an academic, he focuses his research on \"the creative process, ethnography, oral histories, material culture and performativity\".<ref name=Uprising1 /> He is the author of several plays, and as an artist is best known for his first installation, ''The West Indian Front Room'', which was exhibited with great success in 2005, attracting more than 35,000 visitors in its initial outing at the Geffrye Museum, and going on to inspire a [[BBC Four]] documentary called ''Tales from the Front Room'' (2007), a website<ref>[http://www.iniva.org/press/2007/front_room \"Iniva launches the The Front Room website\"], InIVA press release, 15 October 2007.</ref><ref>[http://www.thefrontroom.org.uk/ The Front Room] interactive website.</ref> a 2009 book, ''The Front Room: Migrant Aesthetics in the Home'', and various international commissions, such as ''Van Huis Uit: The Living Room of Migrants in the Netherlands'' (Imagine IC, [[Amsterdam]], and Netherlands Tour, 2007\u201308)<ref>Michael McMillan, [http://www.iniva.net/frontroom/media/files/essays/VHU_GuidedTalk.pdf \"Van Huis Uit/That\u2019s the way we do it\u2026!: The Living Room of Migrants in The Netherlands.\"] Guided Talk, April 2007.</ref> and ''A Living Room Surrounded by Salt'' (IBB, [[Cura\u00e7ao]], 2008).<ref name=\"Uprising interview\" /> A more recent installation of the [[Bogle-L'Ouverture Publications#Bookshop|Walter Rodney Bookshop]] featured as part of the 2015 exhibition ''[[No Colour Bar]]'' at the [[Guildhall Art Gallery]].\n\nMcMillan has said of the range of his work: \"I was a painter before I was a playwright/dramatist and through making live art pieces and writing critically about performance, photography, visual arts culture, I have come home in a sense to fine arts, through making mixed-media installations, which given my interest in performativity background can be seen also as theatre sets. My work and practice is often interdisciplinary using mixed media, installations and performance.\"<ref name=\"Uprising interview\" />\n\n==Life and career==\n\nMichael McMillan was born in 1962 in [[High Wycombe]], UK, of [[Caribbean]] migrant heritage;<ref name=\"Uprising interview\" /> as he has said, \"Both my parents came from [[St Vincent & the Grenadines]] and ... were 'arrivants', to use [[Edward Kamau Brathwaite]]'s term, from colonies where they were imbued with English culture.\"<ref name=Wasafiri>[http://www.wasafiri.org/pages/news_01/news_item.asp?News_01ID=263 \"Michael McMillan reviews - Migrations: Journeys into British Art - Tate Britain 31 Jan - 12 Aug 2012\" (biographical note)], ''[[Wasafiri]]'', 7 March 2012.</ref> Given this background, he has said, \"I grew up with learning three languages: the creole spoken by my parents as a fusion of an English lexicon and an African grammar; the [[Jamaican English]] spoken on the streets of [[London Borough of Hackney|Hackney]] and around London and the London English spoken at school.\"<ref>Michael McMillan, [http://www.ericascourti.com/soundingperformance/michael_mcmillan.html \"Oral Histories in an Ethnographic Context\"], Sounding Performance, November 2007.</ref> He won an essay competition, run by [[Len Garrison]]'s ACER (Afro-Caribbean Education Resource),<ref>[[Mike Phillips (writer)|Mike Phillips]], [https://www.theguardian.com/news/2003/feb/28/guardianobituaries.highereducation \"Obituary: Len Garrison - Recording the history of black Britons for future generations\"], ''[[The Guardian]]'', 28 February 2003.</ref> and after going to [[FESTAC 77]] (the Second World Festival of African Arts and Culture), he wrote his play ''The School Leaver'' (1978), which was produced at the [[Royal Court Theatre]]'s Young Writers' Festival.<ref name=BPArchive>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/playwrights/mcmillan-michael \"Michael McMillan\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n\nMcMillan read sociology and African and Asian studies at [[Sussex University]], graduating in 1984,<ref name=Uprising1>[http://www.uprising-art.com/en/portfolio/michael-mcmillan-st-vincent-uk/ \"Michael McMillan | St. Vincent \u2013 UK\"], Uprising Art, 12 April 2012.</ref> and then earned an MA degree in Independent Film & Video from [[Central Saint Martins]], London, in 1991.<ref name=enroute>[http://www.arts.ac.uk/media/arts/about-ual/diversity/documents/En-Route-Michael-McMillan.pdf \"CSM Alumnus Michael McMillan\"], en>route, UAL.</ref> From 2000, he was a [[Royal Literary Fund]] Writing Fellow<ref>Fellows: [http://www.rlf.org.uk/fellowships/michael-mcmillan/ \"Michael McMillan, Non-fiction writer, Playwright\"], Royal Literary Fund.</ref> at the [[London College of Communication]] and went on to become, since 2003, a Visiting Professor of Creative Writing at the [[University of the Arts London]] (UAL), and a researcher and Associate Lecturer at the [[London College of Fashion]] (LCF), teaching predominantly Cultural & Historical Studies.<ref name=PP /><ref name=enroute /> He was awarded a practice-based Arts Doctorate from [[Middlesex University]] in 2010.<ref name=iniva>[http://www.iniva.org/library/news/clothes_cloth_and_culture_group_sept_2014 \"Clothes, Cloth and Culture Group: 'Saga Bwoys' and Bedouin Women\"], [[InIVA]], 25 September 2014.</ref><ref>[http://placeinternational.org/mcmillan.htm \"Associate Member, Dr Michael McMillan\"], PLaCE (UK).</ref> In 2010\u201311, he was Arts in Health & Well Being artist-in-residence in [[North Wales]].<ref name=Uprising1 />\n\n===Writing===\n\nMcMillan's interest in oral history and the stories of first-generation Caribbean migrants is reflected in early writings such as ''Brother to Brother'' (1996) and ''The Black Boy Pub & Other Stories'' (1997), which used recordings of interviews done during a year's residence in High Wycombe,<ref>Reva Klein, [https://www.tes.com/article.aspx?storycode=56121 \"No place like home\"], ''TES'', 11 May 2008.</ref> where many of those arriving in particular from SVG had settled.<ref>Michael McMillan, [https://books.google.com/books?id=EQkeAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=%22michael+mcmillan%22+born+st+vincent&source=bl&ots=-w2Ap-8S8p&sig=Z0yBa2iG2qO-PLmZktqx9qUXdOo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBWoVChMI7dm8gqeQyAIVTFgaCh3y6AzC#v=onepage&q=%22michael%20mcmillan%22%20born%20st%20vincent&f=false \"De Mudder Tongue: Oral History Work as an Arts Practice\"], in Matthew Partington and Linda Sandino (eds), ''Oral History in the Visual Arts'', A & C Black, 2013 (pp. 25\u201333), p. 26.</ref><ref>Natricia Duncan, [http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/caribbean-island-changed-uk-town \"The Caribbean Island That Changed A UK Town \u2014 How people from St Vincent and the Grenadines transformed life in High Wycombe\"], ''[[The Voice (British newspaper)|The Voice]]'', 28 July 2013.</ref> As a dramatist, he has had work performed and produced by the [[Royal Court Theatre]], [[Channel 4]], [[BBC Radio 4]], and in venues across the UK.<ref name=PP /><ref name=Doollee>[http://www.doollee.com/PlaywrightsM/mcmillan-michael.html Michael McMillan] at Doollee.com.</ref> His play ''The School Leaver'' was published by the [[Black Ink Collective]] in 1978, when McMillan was 16 years old, and was reprinted several times.<ref>Desrie Thomson-George, [https://www.thebookseller.com/blogs/legacy-black-ink-426351 \"The legacy of Black Ink\"], ''[[The Bookseller]]'', 7 November 2016.</ref> His other plays include ''Master Juba'' (2006), ''Babel Junction'' (2006), and a new translation of [[Bertholt Brecht]]'s ''[[The Good Person of Sezuan]]'',<ref>[http://www.arts.ac.uk/chelsea/events/research/taste-conference/speaker-profiles/ \"Speaker profiles: Dr Michael McMillan\"], UAL.</ref> set in [[Jamaica]] in the 1980s.<ref name=Wasafiri />\n\nMcMillan has written a number of essays and articles in national and international publications, and has presented papers at conferences and symposiums in the UK, Europe, Canada, USA, Caribbean and Brazil, including as keynote speaker at the 2006 \"Islands in Between\" Conference on Language, Literature & History of the Eastern Caribbean ([[University of the West Indies]], School of Continuing Studies, St. Vincent & the Grenadines).<ref name=AfroComb />\n\n===Installations===\nAlongside teaching, McMillan has also worked on mixed-media exhibitions and publications. His first installation, ''The West Indian Front Room'' (he uses \"the term 'West Indian' as it refers to a particular moment of post-[[World War II]] Caribbean migration to England and the wider Diaspora\"),<ref name=\"Uprising interview\">Clelia Coussonnet, [http://blog.uprising-art.com/en/exclusive-interview-michael-mcmillan-2/ \"Exclusive Interview: Michael McMillan \u2013 in the framework of the exhibition Who More Sci-Fi than Us\" (May 2012)], Uprising Art, 2 July 2012.</ref> drew on memories of the domestic setting created by his parents and their like after they migrated to Britain, featuring a recreation of a typical front room of the 1970s to raise  \"questions about the constructions of diaspora, identity, race, class and gender in the domestic interior\".<ref>Michael McMillan, [http://www.mona.uwi.edu/conferences/literatures/ABS/ABS%20McMillan.pdf \"The \u2018West Indian\u2019 Front Room: migrant aesthetics in the home\"], University of the West Indies, Mona.</ref> According to cultural theorist [[Stuart Hall (cultural theorist)|Stuart Hall]], \"The front room is a conservative element of black domestic life, which is more complex and rich than the generality of the society ever realises\"; nevertheless, McMillan recalled in an article in ''[[The Guardian]]'': <blockquote>\"Growing up in our front room caused me much aesthetic distress. The wallpaper and carpet never seemed to match, and Jim Reeves would be crooning from the Blue Spot radiogram on a Sunday. This room was based on the Victorian parlour and was inscribed with a formal code of behaviour because it was reserved for receiving guests. It was packed with furniture, ornaments and soft furnishings surrounded by a gallery of pictures and photographs.\"<ref name=Guardian>Michael McMillan, [https://www.theguardian.com/society/2009/sep/16/african-caribbean-immigration-front-rooms-book \"Home is where the art is \u2014 The front rooms of African-Caribbean immigrants to the UK are centre stage in a new book\"], ''The Guardian'', 16 September 2009.</ref></blockquote> Mounted at London's [[Geffrye Museum]] in October 2005, the critically acclaimed exhibition resonated with more than 35,000 visitors who represented a variety of ages, genders and social, cultural and ethnic backgrounds.<ref name=Guardian /> Different versions have since been remade in other countries and cultural settings, including in the Netherlands and in Cura\u00e7ao, and the associated BBC4 television documentary ''Tales from the Front Room'' was broadcast in 2007. He has also made presentations on ''The Front Room'' at the [[University of Wisconsin-Madison]] (2009), [[Clark University]], Worcester (2009) and [[Northwestern University]], [[Chicago]], (2008).<ref name=AfroComb>[http://www.originsoftheafrocomb.co.uk/project/committee.html \"The committee\"], Origins of the Afro Comb.</ref> A book entitled ''The Front Room: Migrant Aesthetics in the Home'' followed in 2009.<ref>Michael McMillan, [http://svgblog.blogspot.co.uk/2009/09/life-before-ikea-by-michael-mcmillan.html \"Life before IKEA\"]; via Karl Eklund, Saint Vincent and the Grenadines blog, 7 September 2009.</ref>\n\nAnother installation-based exhibition was ''The Beauty Shop'' (2008) at the [[198 Contemporary Arts and Learning|198 Gallery]] in south London,<ref>[http://www.198.org.uk/artistic-programmes/archives/beauty-shop \"The Beauty Shop\"], Archives, 198 Contemporary Arts & Learning.</ref> where, as with ''The Front Room'', McMillan \"tried to create a tangible sense of performance. Visitors were encouraged to respond to them as theatre as much as art.\"<ref>Michael McMillan, [https://www.theguardian.com/stage/theatreblog/2009/sep/30/black-theatre-plays-roy-williams \"There's more to black theatre than plays\"], ''The Guardian'', 30 September 2009.</ref>\n\nIn 2015, he recreated the [[Bogle-L'Ouverture Publications#Bookshop|Walter Rodney Bookshop]] as an installation within the exhibition ''[[No Colour Bar: Black British Art in Action 1960\u20131990]]'' at the [[Guildhall Art Gallery]] (July 2015\u2013January 2016),<ref>William Axtell, [http://www.culture24.org.uk/art/art531290-guildlhall-celebrates-black-british-artists-with-no-colour-bar-black-british-art-in-action-1960-1990 \"Guildhall celebrates black British artists with No Colour Bar: Black British Art in Action\"], Culture24, 9 July 2015.</ref> and participated in related events.<ref>[http://artmaplondon.com/artmap/events/radical-readings-from-the-walter-rodney-bookshop-at-the-guildhall-art-gallery-65728/ \"Radical Readings from the Walter Rodney Bookshop at the Guildhall Art Gallery\"], Art Map London, September 2015.</ref><ref>[http://huntleysonline.com/f-h-a-l-m-a/events/ FHALMA \u2014 Events: \"No Colour Bar: Black British Art in Action 1960 \u2013 1990\"], Huntleys Online.</ref><ref>[http://nocolourbar.blogspot.co.uk/2015/08/personal-insight-from-curator-michael.html \"Personal Insight from Curator Michael McMillan\"], No Colour Bar Blogspot, 24 August 2015.</ref>\n\nAnother recent work is ''Doing Nothing Is Not An Option'', a site-responsive mixed-media installation to commemorate the 20th anniversary of the death of [[Ken Saro-Wiwa]] by exploring the relationship between local people in [[Peckham]] and the memory of the [[Nigeria]]n writer and activist.<ref>[http://www.peckhamplatform.com/system/files/082015/55c1fc7b7d636859840004a9/original/Michael_McMillan_Exhibition_PR_FINAL.pdf?1438776443 \"Doing Nothing Is Not An Option\"], Michael McMillan | Peckham Platform | 17 September \u2013 22 November 2015.</ref><ref>[https://vimeo.com/143785039 \"Doing Nothing Is Not An Option\"], video from Peckham Platform.</ref>\n\n==Selected curatorial work==\n* \"My Hair: Black Hair Culture, Style and Politics\" (in ''Origins of the Afro Comb'', Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, 2013)\n* \"I Miss My Mum\u2019s Cooking\" (in ''Who More Sci-Fi Than Us'', KAdE Kunsthal, [[Amersfoort]], [[Netherlands]], 2012)\n* \"The Waiting Room\" (in ''Stories and Journeys'', [[Gwynedd]] Museum & Art Gallery, [[Bangor, Gwynedd|Bangor]], [[North Wales]], 2012)\n* ''The Southall Story'' (South Bank Centre, 2010)\n* ''A Living Room Surrounded by Salt'' (Instituto Buena Bista, [[Cura\u00e7ao]], 2008)\n* ''The Beauty Shop'' (198 Contemporary Arts and Learning, Brixton, 25 January 2008 \u2013 28 March 2013)\n* ''Van Huis Uit: The Living Room of Migrants in the Netherlands'' (Imagine IC, Amsterdam, and Netherlands Tour, 2007\u201308)\n* ''The West Indian Front Room'' (Geffrye Museum, 2005\u201306)<ref>Michael McMillan, [https://www.academia.edu/290317/The_West_Indian_Front_Room_Reflections_on_a_Diasporic_Phenomenon \"The 'West Indian' Front Room: Reflections on a Diasporic Phenomenon\"], ''Small Axe: A Caribbean Journal of Criticism'' (SX 28, Vol. 13, No. 1, March 2009) {{ISSN|0799-0537}}. Abstract, Academia/</ref>\n* \"The Walter Rodney Bookshop\" (in ''No Colour Bar: Black British Art in Action 1960\u20131990'', Guildhall Art Gallery, 10 July 2015 \u2013 24 January 2016)\n\n==Selected publications==\n* ''The Waiting Room: An audio-visual tale of an artist in residence at the Alaw Ward (Cancer & Palliative Care Unit) in Ysbyty Gwynedd & Rheumatology Clinics in Ysbyty Gwynedd and Ysbyty Llandudno'' (2006)\n* ''Same Difference: 25 Years of International Youth Volunteering with the Daneford Trust'' (2006).\n* ''Living Proof: Views of a World Living with HIV/AIDS'' (Artist Agency, 1992).\n* ''The Black Boy Pub & Other Stories: The black experience in High Wycombe'' (Wycombe District Council, 1997).\n* ''Growing Up Is Hard To Do: A Book For Young People & Adults About Sexual Health'' (Young People's Health Project, 2000).\n* ''The Front Room: Migrant Aesthetics in the Home'' (Black Dog Publishing, 2009, {{ISBN|978-1906155858}})<ref>Michael McMillan, [https://www.amazon.co.uk/dp/1906155852 ''The Front Room'' (2009)] at Amazon.</ref>\n* ''If I Could Fly: An anthology of writings from young men at Orchard Lodge Resource Centre'' (Southwark Social Services, 1998).\n* Editor, ''Words, Sounds & Power Anthology'' (Centerprise Publishing Project, 1988)\n* ''On Duty'' (Akira Press, 1984)<ref name=\"BPArchive\"/>\n*''The School Leaver'' ([[Black Ink Collective]], 1978)<ref name=AfroComb />\n\n==Plays and performance pieces==\n* New translation of ''[[The Good Person of Sezuan]]'' by [[Bertolt Brecht]] (2010 & 2012)<ref name=Doollee />\n* ''Babel Junction'' ([[Hackney Empire|Empire Theatre]], 2006)<ref name=Doollee /><ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/babel-junctions \"Babel Junctions\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''Master Juba'' (Luton Library Theatre, Albany Theatre, 2006)<ref name=Doollee /><ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/master-juba \"Master Juba\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''Can you Play Football?'' (2004)\n* ''Blood for Britain'' (BBC Radio 4 Drama, 2001) \n* ''After Windrush'' ([[Oval House Theatre]], 1998)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/after-windrush \"After Windrush\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''Brother to Brother'' ([[Lyric Hammersmith]] and tour, 1996 & 1998); in Cheryl Robson (ed.), ''Black and Asian Plays Anthology'', Aurora Metro, 2000<ref name=Doollee /><ref>Susan Croft, [http://media.vam.ac.uk/media/documents/legacy_documents/file_upload/37047_file.pdf?q=plays \"Black Playwrights in Britain in Print\" (bibliography)], VAM.</ref><ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/brother-brother \"Brother To Brother\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''I Hope It's Not a Black Man'' (1996)\n* ''Invisible'' (Double Edge Theatre Company; 1993 & 1998)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/invisible \"Invisible\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''The Last Blind Date'' (Artists Alliance/Live Theatre, 1992)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/last-blind-date \"Last Blind Date, The\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''Portrait of a Shopping Centre as a Cathedral'' (1990)\n* ''First Impressions'' (Perspective Theatre Company, 1988)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/first-impressions \"First Impressions\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''On Duty'' (Carlton Centre, Kilburn, 1983)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/duty \"On Duty\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n* ''Carve Your Name'' ([[The Old Vic Theatre]], 1981)\n* ''Day of Action'' (Brent Black People's Theatre, 1981)\n* ''Hard Time Pressure'' ([[Royal Court Theatre]], 1980)\n* ''The School Leaver'' (Royal Court Theatre, 1978)<ref>[http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/productions/school-leaver \"The School Leaver\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.uprising-art.com/en/portfolio/michael-mcmillan-st-vincent-uk/ \"Michael McMillan | St. Vincent \u2013 UK\"], Uprising Art.\n* [http://blog.uprising-art.com/exclusive-interview-michael-mcmillan/ \"Exclusive Interview: Michael McMillan \u2013 in the framework of the exhibition Who More Sci-Fi than Us\"], Uprising Art, 2 July 2012.\n* [http://www.blackplaysarchive.org.uk/explore/playwrights/mcmillan-michael \"Michael McMillan\"], Black Plays Archive, National Theatre.\n* [http://www.doollee.com/PlaywrightsM/mcmillan-michael.html Michael McMillan] at Doollee.com.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TVM6vAEGv64 \"Artist Shiraz Bayjoo In Conversation with Michael McMillan, 5 Feb 2015\"], InivaArts. YouTube.\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McMillan, Michael}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Black British artists]]\n[[Category:Black British writers]]\n[[Category:Black British academics]]\n[[Category:English people of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines descent]]\n[[Category:British curators]]\n[[Category:English curators]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Sussex]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Central Saint Martins]]\n[[Category:Academics of the University of the Arts London]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "WhartonUndergrad", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_McMillan"}
